    ray.recreate(x)  # Rerun the task that created x.

@istoica Sure. Let's say the original class is 
```java
class Counter {
    private int value;
    public int incr(int delta) {
        value += delta;
        return value;
    }
}
```
If user annotate it with `@RayActor`, the following class will be generated:
```java
class CounterActor {
    public static CounterActor create() {
        // create a remote actor and return a local actor handler
    }
    public RayObject<Integer> incr(int delta) {
        // put parameters and submit task
    }
    public RayObject<Integer> incr(RayObject<Integer> delta) { // same here }
}
```
Then user can use this like this:
```java
CounterActor c = CounterActor.create();
RayObject<Integer> res = c.incr(1);
res.get();
```

PS1: the reason why there're 2 different annotations is because both annotations decorate classes (Java doesn't have standalone functions).
PS2: it makes sense to use 2^N as default. It's also fine to not provide the option first.

I don't currently have anything equivalent to Grappelli's `onBeforeAdded` hook, though I could add one if necessary. First I would try using the [`formset:added`](http://django-nested-admin.readthedocs.io/en/latest/customization.html#events) event and see if you can deinitialize and reinitialize the TinyMCE editor with just that. You would add something like the following to a static file in your app that you include with your `class Media` on the admin.

```javascript
(function($) {
    $(document).on('formset:added', function(event, $form) {
        if (window.tinyMCE) {
          deselector = tinyMCE.settings.editor_deselector;
          $form.find('textarea:not(.' + deselector + ')').each(function() {
            var id = $(this).attr('id');
            tinyMCE.execCommand('mceRemoveControl', false, id);
            tinyMCE.execCommand('mceAddControl', false, id);
          });
        }
    })
})(django.jQuery);
```

